🧠 OS Concept 1: Trap vs Interrupt vs System Call (VERY CONFUSING 🔥)

This is a favorite interview trap question

1️⃣ Simple Idea

All 3 mean:

👉 CPU changes normal execution

But WHY they occur is different

🧠 Core Difference
Type	Who triggers	Why
Interrupt	Hardware	external event
Trap	CPU	error or exception
System Call	Program	request OS
🧠 Real-World Analogy

You studying 📚:

Phone rings → Interrupt
You make mistake → Trap
You ask teacher → System Call
⚙️ Deep Understanding
🔹 Interrupt

From devices:

keyboard
mouse
disk

👉 asynchronous

🔹 Trap

From CPU:

divide by zero
invalid instruction

👉 synchronous

🔹 System Call

From program:

read(), write()

👉 controlled request

🔗 Connection

System call uses:

👉 trap mechanism internally

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Difference between interrupt and trap?

👉 Interrupt = external
👉 Trap = internal

🧠 Memory Trick
Interrupt = outside
Trap = inside error
Syscall = request
🧠 OS Concept 2: Preemptive vs Non-Preemptive Scheduling

🔥 VERY COMMON QUESTION

1️⃣ Simple Idea

👉 Can OS take CPU away from process or not?

⚙️ Types
🔹 Non-Preemptive

👉 Once process starts → runs until finish

Example:

FCFS
SJF

❌ Poor responsiveness

🔹 Preemptive

👉 OS can interrupt process anytime

Example:

Round Robin

✔ Better responsiveness

🧠 Real-World Analogy
Non-preemptive

One person talks fully in meeting

Preemptive

Teacher interrupts:

👉 “Time’s up, next!”

🔗 Connection to Context Switching

Preemptive → more context switches

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Why preemptive scheduling is better?

👉 improves responsiveness and fairness

🧠 Memory Trick
Preemptive = interrupt allowed
Non-preemptive = no interruption
⚙️ COA Concept 3: Throughput vs Latency (IMPORTANT)
1️⃣ Simple Idea

Two performance measures:

👉 Throughput = how many tasks done
👉 Latency = time for one task

🧠 Real-World Analogy

Restaurant 🍽️

Throughput → customers per hour
Latency → time for one order
⚙️ Example

System A:

10 tasks/sec (high throughput)
5 sec per task (high latency)

System B:

5 tasks/sec
2 sec per task
🔗 Connection to Performance (Day 9)

Both define system performance

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Difference between throughput and latency?

👉 Throughput = total work
👉 Latency = time per work

🧠 Memory Trick
Throughput = quantity
Latency = delay
⚙️ COA Concept 4: Speedup & Efficiency
1️⃣ Simple Idea

Speedup =
👉 how much faster system becomes

Efficiency =
👉 how well resources are used

🔥 Core Formula

Speedup
=
Time (old)
Time (new)
Speedup=
Time (new)
Time (old)
	​


🧠 Meaning

If:

Old time = 10 sec
New time = 5 sec

👉 Speedup = 2

⚙️ Efficiency
Efficiency = Speedup / Number of processors
🔗 Connection to Amdahl’s Law (Day 11)

Speedup is limited due to:

👉 sequential part

🎯 Placement Question

Q: What is speedup?

👉 Ratio of old execution time to new execution time.

🧠 Memory Trick
Speedup = faster factor
Efficiency = usage quality
